  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>How to Calculate Gravel</h2>
    <p>Calculating the right amount of gravel for any project starts with three measurements: length, width, and depth. Whether you are building a driveway, laying a garden path, or creating a drainage bed, the formula is straightforward. Accurate measurements prevent over-ordering, which wastes money, and under-ordering, which delays your project and may incur additional delivery fees.</p>
    <p>The basic formula converts your three-dimensional measurements into a volume, expressed in cubic yards, which is the standard unit for ordering bulk landscaping and construction materials in the United States. One cubic yard equals 27 cubic feet, which is a volume measuring 3 feet long by 3 feet wide by 3 feet deep.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <code>Cubic Yards = (Length ft &times; Width ft &times; Depth in / 12) / 27</code>
    </div>
    <p>Begin by measuring the length and width of the area in feet. If the area is irregular, break it into smaller rectangles, calculate each one separately, and add the volumes together. For circular areas, use the formula for the area of a circle (pi times the radius squared) in place of the length times width calculation.</p>
    <p>Next, determine the desired depth of gravel in inches. Different applications call for different depths, which we will discuss in detail below. Convert the depth from inches to feet by dividing by 12. For example, 3 inches becomes 0.25 feet and 6 inches becomes 0.5 feet.</p>
    <p>Multiply the length by the width by the depth in feet to get the total volume in cubic feet. Divide by 27 to convert to cubic yards. For example, a patio area measuring 20 feet long by 10 feet wide at 3 inches deep requires 20 times 10 times 0.25 equals 50 cubic feet, divided by 27 equals 1.85 cubic yards.</p>
    <p>To determine the weight in tons, multiply the cubic yards by the density of the gravel type you are using. Crushed stone, for instance, weighs approximately 1.4 tons per cubic yard, so 1.85 cubic yards would weigh about 2.59 tons. Knowing the tonnage is essential because many suppliers price and deliver gravel by the ton rather than by the cubic yard.</p>
    <p>Finally, it is wise to add 5 to 10 percent extra material to your order. Gravel settles and compacts over time, some material will inevitably be lost during spreading and grading, and minor measurement inaccuracies can leave you short. Ordering a little extra now is far cheaper than arranging a second delivery later.</p>

    <h2>Gravel Types and Uses</h2>
    <p>Not all gravel is the same. Each type varies in size, shape, texture, color, weight, and price. Selecting the right gravel depends on the specific application, the aesthetic you want, the amount of foot or vehicle traffic the area will receive, and your budget. Below is a detailed comparison of the five most popular gravel types.</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Gravel Type</th>
          <th>Size</th>
          <th>Weight per Cubic Yard</th>
          <th>Cost per Ton</th>
          <th>Best Uses</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Pea Gravel</td>
          <td>1/8" - 3/8"</td>
          <td>1.35 tons (2,700 lbs)</td>
          <td>$35 - $55</td>
          <td>Walkways, patios, playgrounds, garden beds</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Crushed Stone</td>
          <td>1/2" - 1"</td>
          <td>1.4 tons (2,800 lbs)</td>
          <td>$30 - $50</td>
          <td>Driveways, road base, foundations, drainage</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>River Rock</td>
          <td>1" - 3"</td>
          <td>1.3 tons (2,600 lbs)</td>
          <td>$40 - $80</td>
          <td>Decorative landscaping, dry creek beds, borders</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Decomposed Granite</td>
          <td>Fine - 1/4"</td>
          <td>1.35 tons (2,700 lbs)</td>
          <td>$25 - $50</td>
          <td>Pathways, xeriscaping, patio surfaces, fill</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Marble Chips</td>
          <td>1/2" - 1"</td>
          <td>1.3 tons (2,600 lbs)</td>
          <td>$70 - $120</td>
          <td>Decorative accents, garden borders, monuments</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p><strong>Pea gravel</strong> consists of small, naturally rounded stones that are smooth to the touch and comfortable to walk on barefoot. The rounded shape means pea gravel does not lock together or compact tightly, making it a poor choice for driveways where vehicle tires can displace the stones. However, it is an excellent choice for walkways, patios, dog runs, and playgrounds where its smooth texture and drainage properties are assets. Pea gravel is available in a range of earth-tone colors including tan, brown, gray, and white.</p>
    <p><strong>Crushed stone</strong> is mechanically broken rock with angular, irregular edges that interlock and compact firmly under pressure. This interlocking property makes crushed stone the most popular choice for driveways, parking areas, road base courses, and any surface that must support vehicle traffic. Crushed limestone, crushed granite, and trap rock are the most common varieties. Crushed stone is also widely used as a drainage material beneath foundations, behind retaining walls, and in French drains because it allows water to flow freely through the gaps between stones.</p>
    <p><strong>River rock</strong> is naturally smoothed stone collected from riverbeds and lake shores. Stones are larger than pea gravel, typically 1 to 3 inches in diameter, though jumbo river rock can exceed 5 inches. River rock is primarily a decorative material used in landscaping, dry creek beds, water features, and garden borders. Its smooth, polished appearance adds a natural, refined look to any landscape. Because the stones are large and heavy, river rock resists displacement by wind and water better than smaller gravels.</p>
    <p><strong>Decomposed granite</strong> is granite rock that has weathered and broken down into a mix of fine particles and small fragments. When compacted, it creates a firm, stable surface with a natural, rustic appearance. Decomposed granite is widely used in the western United States for pathways, patios, and xeriscaping. It can be stabilized with a resin binder to create a surface that is nearly as hard as concrete while maintaining its natural look. Without stabilizer, decomposed granite can become muddy in wet conditions and may need periodic regrading.</p>
    <p><strong>Marble chips</strong> are the premium option, produced by crushing natural marble stone. They are bright white or lightly veined and create a striking visual contrast in garden beds, around tree bases, and alongside walkways. Marble chips are significantly more expensive than other gravel types, so they are typically used for smaller decorative areas rather than large-scale projects. Over time, marble chips can lose some brightness due to weathering and may benefit from periodic rinsing.</p>

    <h2>How Deep Should Gravel Be?</h2>
    <p>The correct depth of gravel depends entirely on the intended application. Installing gravel too shallow leads to thin spots, exposed fabric or soil, and poor performance. Installing gravel too deep wastes money and material. Below are the recommended depths for the most common gravel applications.</p>
    <p><strong>Driveways (4-6 inches):</strong> Residential gravel driveways should be 4 to 6 inches deep after compaction. Most professionals recommend a 3-layer system. The bottom layer is 4 inches of coarse crushed stone (1.5 to 2.5 inches) that serves as the structural base. The middle layer is 2 to 3 inches of mid-size crushed stone (about 3/4 inch) that fills gaps and adds stability. The top layer is 1 to 2 inches of fine crushed stone or stone dust that creates a smooth driving surface. For driveways that receive heavy traffic or heavy vehicles, increase the base layer to 6 inches.</p>
    <p><strong>Walkways (2-3 inches):</strong> Garden walkways and foot paths require 2 to 3 inches of gravel over a compacted base and landscape fabric. Pea gravel and decomposed granite are the most popular choices for walkways because they are comfortable to walk on and create an attractive surface. Edge restraints such as metal landscape edging, stone borders, or pressure-treated wood are essential for keeping walkway gravel from spreading into adjacent garden beds and lawn areas.</p>
    <p><strong>Patios (3-4 inches):</strong> Gravel patios should be 3 to 4 inches deep over compacted soil and landscape fabric. For a more stable surface that resists furniture legs sinking in, use crushed stone or stabilized decomposed granite instead of pea gravel. A well-compacted gravel patio provides excellent drainage and can be more affordable to install than a paver or concrete patio. Add a border of larger stones or pavers to define the patio edges and contain the gravel.</p>
    <p><strong>Drainage applications (6-12 inches):</strong> French drains, dry wells, and other drainage installations require 6 to 12 inches of gravel depending on the volume of water being managed. Crushed stone in the 3/4 inch to 1.5 inch range is ideal for drainage because it creates large voids for water to flow through. Avoid using fine gravel or stone dust for drainage, as small particles fill the voids and impede water flow. Wrap the gravel in filter fabric to prevent soil from migrating into the drainage bed and clogging it over time.</p>
    <p><strong>Garden beds and landscaping (2-3 inches):</strong> Decorative gravel in garden beds and around shrubs should be 2 to 3 inches deep over landscape fabric. This depth suppresses weeds, retains soil moisture, and provides full coverage without looking excessively thick. River rock, marble chips, and decorative pea gravel are popular choices for garden beds because they offer visual appeal and do not decompose like organic mulches.</p>

    <h2>Tips for Ordering Gravel</h2>
    <p>Ordering the right amount of gravel at the best price requires a bit of planning. These practical tips will help you avoid common pitfalls and ensure your project goes smoothly from purchase to installation.</p>
    <p><strong>Order 5-10 percent extra.</strong> Gravel compacts and settles after installation, minor amounts are lost during spreading, and measurements are rarely perfect. Ordering a small surplus is much cheaper than paying for a second delivery. For large projects like driveways, lean toward 10 percent extra. For smaller contained areas with defined edges, 5 percent is usually sufficient.</p>
    <p><strong>Buy in bulk for large projects.</strong> Bulk gravel is sold by the ton or cubic yard and delivered by dump truck. It costs significantly less per ton than bagged gravel. Bulk delivery typically costs $30 to $50 per ton plus a delivery fee of $50 to $150 depending on distance. For projects requiring more than 1 to 2 tons, bulk delivery is almost always the more economical option.</p>
    <p><strong>Compare prices from multiple suppliers.</strong> Gravel prices vary widely between suppliers, even in the same area. Landscape supply yards, quarries, and garden centers may each offer different pricing. Some suppliers offer free delivery above a minimum order, which can tip the balance in their favor. Get at least three quotes before committing to a supplier.</p>
    <p><strong>Verify your delivery site is accessible.</strong> Dump trucks require a firm, relatively flat area to unload material. Ensure the truck can reach the drop zone without driving over septic systems, irrigation lines, underground utilities, or soft ground that could cause the truck to get stuck. Identify where you want the gravel pile placed and clear the area in advance. The closer you can get the pile to the work area, the less wheelbarrowing you will need to do.</p>
    <p><strong>Consider timing and seasonality.</strong> Gravel prices and availability can fluctuate seasonally. Spring and summer are peak demand periods for landscaping materials, so prices may be slightly higher and delivery times longer. Ordering in late fall or early winter can sometimes yield better pricing, though weather conditions may limit your installation window. Many suppliers offer discounts for large orders placed during the off-season.</p>
    <p><strong>Ask about washed vs. unwashed gravel.</strong> Washed gravel has been cleaned to remove fine dust and dirt, resulting in a cleaner appearance and better drainage. Unwashed gravel includes fine particles that help it compact better, making it suitable for base layers and driveways. Washed gravel costs slightly more but is worth the premium for decorative applications where appearance matters.</p>

    <h2>Gravel Installation Steps</h2>
    <p>Installing a gravel surface is a manageable weekend project for most homeowners, but proper preparation is critical for a result that looks professional and lasts for years. Skipping preparation steps, particularly compaction and fabric installation, leads to weed growth, uneven settling, and a surface that looks neglected within a year. Follow these steps for a successful installation.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 1: Mark and excavate the area.</strong> Use stakes and string or spray paint to mark the boundaries of your gravel area. Excavate the soil to the total depth of the gravel plus 2 to 4 inches for a compacted base. For a walkway with 3 inches of gravel, you would dig down approximately 5 to 7 inches. Remove all vegetation, roots, and large rocks from the excavated area. Grade the bottom of the excavation to slope slightly away from any structures for drainage, typically at a rate of 1/4 inch per foot.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 2: Install edging.</strong> Edge restraints keep gravel contained within the designated area and prevent stones from migrating into the lawn or garden beds. Options include metal landscape edging, plastic edging, pressure-treated timber borders, natural stone borders, and concrete curbing. Install the edging to the finished grade height so it holds the gravel in place while remaining flush with the surrounding landscape. Secure metal and plastic edging with landscape spikes every 12 to 18 inches.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 3: Compact the subgrade.</strong> Use a plate compactor or hand tamper to compact the exposed soil at the bottom of the excavation. Compacting the subgrade prevents future settling and provides a stable foundation for the gravel. For driveways and areas that will support vehicle traffic, this step is especially important. If the soil is soft or clay-based, consider adding 2 to 4 inches of compactible base material such as crusher run before laying the gravel.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 4: Lay landscape fabric.</strong> Roll out commercial-grade landscape fabric over the compacted subgrade, overlapping seams by at least 6 inches. The fabric prevents weeds from growing up through the gravel while still allowing water to drain through. Avoid using cheap, thin plastic sheeting, which traps water, suffocates soil organisms, and tears easily. Pin the fabric in place with landscape staples every 12 to 24 inches and along all edges.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 5: Spread and level the gravel.</strong> Pour or dump the gravel onto the landscape fabric and spread it evenly using a rake. Work in manageable sections, spreading the material to the desired depth. Use a level or a straight board laid across the surface to check for high and low spots. Fill low areas and scrape down high spots until the surface is even. For driveways, use a landscaping rake to create a slight crown in the center of the drive so water sheds to the sides rather than pooling on the surface.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 6: Compact the gravel.</strong> For crushed stone and decomposed granite, use a plate compactor to compact the gravel after spreading. Compaction locks the angular stones together, creating a firm, stable surface that resists displacement. Run the compactor in overlapping passes across the entire area. Smooth, rounded gravels like pea gravel and river rock do not compact effectively and should simply be raked to a level surface. Lightly mist crushed stone or decomposed granite with water before compacting to improve binding.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 7: Inspect and maintain.</strong> After installation, inspect the surface for any uneven areas, exposed fabric, or thin spots. Add additional gravel as needed to achieve uniform coverage. In the first few weeks, the gravel may shift and settle as it is walked or driven on. Check periodically and redistribute material with a rake. Annual maintenance typically involves raking the surface to redistribute gravel, adding a thin topping layer to replace material lost to displacement, and removing any weeds that manage to grow through gaps in the fabric.</p>

    <h2>Gravel Cost Estimating Guide</h2>
    <p>Understanding gravel pricing helps you budget accurately for your project. Gravel costs depend on the type of stone, the quantity ordered, your distance from the quarry or supplier, and your geographic region. Here is a breakdown of typical pricing to help you plan.</p>
    <p>Most gravel is priced by the ton for bulk orders. Pea gravel typically runs $35 to $55 per ton, making it a mid-range option that balances aesthetics with affordability. Crushed stone is often the most economical structural gravel at $30 to $50 per ton and is the standard choice for driveways and base courses. River rock is more expensive at $40 to $80 per ton due to its decorative appeal and the cost of collection and processing. Decomposed granite is one of the most affordable options at $25 to $50 per ton and is widely used in arid climates. Marble chips command a premium price of $70 to $120 per ton, reflecting the cost of the raw marble material.</p>
    <p>Delivery fees are a significant additional cost that should be factored into your budget. Most suppliers charge $50 to $150 per delivery depending on the distance from the quarry or supply yard to your property. Some suppliers offer free delivery on orders exceeding a minimum quantity, such as 5 tons or 3 cubic yards. Consolidating your order into a single delivery saves money compared to splitting it into multiple smaller loads.</p>
    <p>Bagged gravel from home improvement stores costs considerably more per ton than bulk gravel. A typical 50-pound bag of gravel costs $4 to $8, which translates to roughly $160 to $320 per ton. Bagged gravel makes sense for very small projects under a few hundred pounds, where the convenience of buying individual bags outweighs the per-ton premium. For anything larger, bulk delivery is significantly more cost-effective.</p>
    <p>To estimate the total cost of your project, use our calculator to determine the tonnage needed, multiply by the per-ton cost for your chosen gravel type, and add the delivery fee. For a typical residential driveway requiring 10 tons of crushed stone at $40 per ton plus a $100 delivery fee, the total gravel cost would be approximately $500. This does not include costs for landscape fabric, edging, base material, equipment rental, or labor if you hire a contractor. Professional installation typically adds $1 to $3 per square foot on top of the material costs.</p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How much gravel do I need for my driveway?</summary>
        <p>Measure the length and width of the driveway in feet and multiply by the desired depth in feet. For most residential driveways, a depth of 4 to 6 inches after compaction is recommended. Divide the total cubic feet by 27 to convert to cubic yards, then multiply by the density of the gravel type to get tons. For example, a 50-foot-long, 12-foot-wide driveway at 4 inches deep requires 50 times 12 times 0.33 equals 198 cubic feet, divided by 27 equals 7.33 cubic yards, times 1.4 (crushed stone density) equals about 10.3 tons. Add 10 percent for compaction and waste, bringing the order to roughly 11.3 tons. At an average cost of $40 per ton for crushed stone, the material cost would be approximately $452 before delivery fees.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How many tons of gravel are in a cubic yard?</summary>
        <p>The conversion from cubic yards to tons depends on the density of the specific gravel type. Crushed stone is the densest common gravel at approximately 1.4 tons per cubic yard, or about 2,800 pounds. Pea gravel and decomposed granite weigh about 1.35 tons per cubic yard, roughly 2,700 pounds. River rock and marble chips are slightly lighter at around 1.3 tons per cubic yard, approximately 2,600 pounds. These are average densities and can vary based on moisture content, stone composition, and particle size distribution. When in doubt, ask your supplier for the specific density of the material they sell, as locally sourced stone may differ from these averages.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How deep should gravel be for a walkway?</summary>
        <p>For walkways, a gravel depth of 2 to 3 inches over landscape fabric and a compacted base is recommended. Pea gravel and decomposed granite are the most popular choices for walkways because they are comfortable underfoot and create an attractive surface. If the walkway receives heavy foot traffic, lean toward 3 inches to ensure adequate coverage over time as the material shifts and compacts. Always install edge restraints such as metal landscape edging, stone borders, or timber edges to keep the gravel contained within the walkway boundaries. For wheelchair accessibility, use compacted decomposed granite or stabilized gravel rather than loose pea gravel or river rock, which can make wheeled travel difficult.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the cheapest type of gravel?</summary>
        <p>Decomposed granite and crushed stone are generally the most affordable gravel options. Decomposed granite ranges from $25 to $50 per ton and is widely available in the western United States. Crushed stone, including crushed limestone and recycled concrete aggregate, costs $30 to $50 per ton and is the most commonly available gravel nationwide. For very tight budgets, recycled concrete aggregate and reclaimed asphalt millings can be even less expensive at $15 to $30 per ton, though they lack the natural appearance of traditional gravel. The cheapest per-ton price does not always mean the cheapest project cost since heavier gravels require more tonnage to cover the same volume.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Do I need landscape fabric under gravel?</summary>
        <p>Yes, landscape fabric is strongly recommended under all gravel installations. The fabric prevents weeds from growing up through the gravel, stops the gravel from sinking into the soil over time, and helps separate the gravel layer from the underlying dirt. Without fabric, weeds will eventually push through even thick gravel layers, and the stones will gradually mix with the soil, reducing both the appearance and functionality of the surface. Use commercial-grade woven landscape fabric rated for the application. Avoid thin plastic sheeting, which does not allow water to drain and will trap moisture beneath the gravel, potentially creating drainage problems and encouraging muddy conditions.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
